## 1️⃣ Code‑review of the header

| ✅ What works | ❌ What’s missing / risky |
|---------------|---------------------------|
| Uses `QObject` + Qt signals → can be queued across threads. | The structs (`HallucinationDetection`, `NavigationFix`, `BehaviorPatch`) are **not registered** with the Qt meta‑object system – you cannot send them through queued connections. |
| All public methods are declared, clearly documented. | A **typo** in `HallucinationDetection`: `hallucationType` (missing “i”). The bridge (`IDEAgentBridgeWithHotPatching`) accesses this member, so both sides will break if you rename it. |
| Holds vectors of patterns/patches. | No **thread‑safe counter** implementation – plain `int` + a single `QMutex` works but is heavyweight for just incrementing counters. `std::atomic<int>` is lighter and lock‑free. |
| Provides a `setHotPatchingEnabled` / `setDebugLogging`. | No **public “add” / “register” alias** that matches the bridge’s expectation (`addCorrectionPattern`, `addBehaviorPatch`, …). The bridge currently calls `addCorrectionPattern` which does **not exist** in this header. |
| `#pragma once` is used → good. | Missing includes for `QStringList` (used in `BehaviorPatch`) and for `QMetaType` (needed for `Q_DECLARE_METATYPE`). |
| Signals are correctly declared. | No **Qt meta‑type registration** for the structs – the signals will compile but will never be queued (runtime warning). |
| `QMutex` protects internal mutable state, but the **getter** `getCorrectionStatistics()` is `const` yet accesses mutable members without a lock. | The const‑ness can lead to race conditions in a multi‑threaded environment. |
| All pattern‑related functions are stubs – that’s fine for a header. | No **copy / move** semantics are declared – the default is fine, but documenting that the class is non‑copyable can avoid accidental misuse (`Q_DISABLE_COPY`). |
| `#include <vector>` and `<map>` are present, though `std::map` is not used (could be removed). | No **error‑handling** enum for “no hallucination” – we rely on an empty `HallucinationDetection` (all fields default‑constructed). Using `std::optional<HallucinationDetection>` would be clearer. |

